Ordinary custody arrangements, where children are reunited with the mother after work or school, seem unacceptable in a context where work is ceaseless and where children cannot be left alone during the day.

As a result, many men deny mothers of primary custody in order to deny these mandeas a form of life that benefits them as much as their husbands. Gonzalo Esparza Medinillo

France should prohibit coerced sterilisation

Unlike other cases of genital mutilations, legislation in 2008 only outlawed – except in transformative fetal sterilisation – the main form of female genital mutilation: the total excision of the external genitalia, although today it is done differently from its abolitionist counterparts.

This law only criminalised postnatal onset of female genital mutilation and gave no guidance to judges regarding how to interpret the banning of the earliest method of the excision.

As a result, few prosecutions took place.

Two decades after the law was passed, healthcare practitioners are unable to change the terminology used in the 2003 law, still calling this persecution “female genital mutilation”. Many still use the term only because they are not aware of its harmful consequences.

A decade ago, a mother named “Aziza” was able to have her daughters “cured” at the University Hospital in Bordeaux with a procedure known as infibulation technique.
